# Remove overlaps - Updated for new multi-tile indices
# This prevents 1x1 tiles (1-9, 16) from overlapping with larger tiles
# Define the set of multi-tile indices
# Multi = 17, 112, 160 (2x1), 19, 114, 162 (3x1), 22, 117, 165 (4x1), 33, 128 (2x2)
# Add indices for 3x3, 4x4 if available
# For simplicity, using 'MultiIndices' placeholder. Replace this in practice if the tool allows aliases or list all explicitly.
# Assuming the tool requires explicit listing: MultiIndices = 17 OR 112 OR 160 OR 19 OR 114 OR 162 OR 22 OR 117 OR 165 OR 33 OR 128 (add 3x3/4x4 indices here)

# --- Start Overlap Rules ---
# Use Index 1-9 and 16 for the primary index check (tiles to be potentially removed)
# Check against the new multi-tile indices at relevant relative positions

# Example rule structure (repeat for all necessary Pos combinations and Index 1-9, 16):
# Index [1-9, 16]
# Pos 0 0 INDEX [MultiIndices] # Check if this spot should be part of a larger block originating elsewhere
# Pos [relative coords] INDEX [MultiIndices] # Check if a larger block originates nearby covering this spot

# --- Adapting original overlap logic structure ---
# The original logic checked Index 16 against potential overlaps within a 3x3 area
# Applying this to the new multi-tile set:
# Replace '3 OR 5 OR 80 OR 67 OR 99' with the new list:
# '17 OR 112 OR 160 OR 19 OR 114 OR 162 OR 22 OR 117 OR 165 OR 33 OR 128' (add 3x3, 4x4 if known)

Index 1 # Target 1x1 tile
Pos 0 0 INDEX 17 OR 112 OR 160 OR 19 OR 114 OR 162 OR 22 OR 117 OR 165 OR 33 OR 128
Pos -1 0 INDEX 17 OR 112 OR 160 OR 19 OR 114 OR 162 OR 22 OR 117 OR 165 OR 33 OR 128 # Check left

Index 1 # Target 1x1 tile
Pos 0 0 INDEX 17 OR 112 OR 160 OR 19 OR 114 OR 162 OR 22 OR 117 OR 165 OR 33 OR 128
Pos 0 -1 INDEX 17 OR 112 OR 160 OR 19 OR 114 OR 162 OR 22 OR 117 OR 165 OR 33 OR 128 # Check up

Index 1 # Target 1x1 tile
Pos 0 0 INDEX 17 OR 112 OR 160 OR 19 OR 114 OR 162 OR 22 OR 117 OR 165 OR 33 OR 128
Pos -1 -1 INDEX 17 OR 112 OR 160 OR 19 OR 114 OR 162 OR 22 OR 117 OR 165 OR 33 OR 128 # Check top-left

# ... (Repeat similar rules for Index 1-9, 16 and various Pos combinations to cover potential overlaps from all directions based on the size of the larger blocks. The original file checked a 3x3 area[cite: 4, 5, 6, 7, 8, 9, 10]. You'll need to expand this checking area based on your largest block size (e.g., 4x1 or potential 4x4)).

# --- Example using original file's structure with new indices ---
# Repeat this block for Index 1-9 as well

